# Persuasion for Dummies

- Establish credibility in the eyes of the listener
  - Be perceived as wise, moral, strong, or inspirational
- Appeal to the listener's emotions
  - Induce feelings of anger, fear, hope, pride
- Use logical reasoning to advance an argument

---

class: center, middle, inverse
background-color: black

<img src="resources/images/aristotle.png" style="position: absolute; left: -10%; width: 60%; top: 0%;"/>

--

<p style="position: absolute; top: 30%; left: 40%; width: 50%; text-align: left;">
  <!-- <i> -->
    "Of the modes of persuasion furnished by the spoken word there are three
    kinds. The first kind depends on the personal character of the speaker; the
    second on putting the audience into a certain frame of mind; the third on the
    proof, or apparent proof, provided by the words of the speech itself."
<!-- </i> -->
</p>

--

<p style="position: absolute; top: 85%; right: 10%; width: 80%; text-align: right;">Aristotle, <i>Rhetoric</i></p>

